Diagnosis
. 

Amblycerus dispar

is characterized by the following combination of characters: eyes closer to each another anteriorly, ocular index: 9.5 (
Fig. 23
); median lobe of male genitalia about 4.5 times as long as its greatest width at apical region and internal sac at the apical region without sclerites (
Fig. 92
). It differs from 

A. schwarzi

by the presence of a frontal carina (absent in 

A. schwarzi

), cervical boss with three setae (two setae in 

A. schwarzi

), metaventrite with median sulcus longer than a half the length of the metaventrite (about half the length of the metaventrite in 

A. schwarzi

), last ventrite almost as long as ventrite IV (almost two times as long as ventrite IV in 

A. schwarzi

) and internal sac of male genitalia without a pair of sclerite at the apical region (one pair in 

A. schwarzi

). 

Amblycerus dispar

can be futher separated from 

A. crassipunctatus

by the presence of frontal carina (absent in 

A. crassipunctatus

), eyes closer to each other anteriorly (
Fig. 23
) (distant in 

A. crassipunctatus

), and metaventrite with median sulcus longer than a half the length of metaventrite (about half the length of metaventrite in 

A. crassipunctatus

).
